As the mystery deepens around the COVID-19 National Command Council, the presidency insists there's nothing untoward or illegal about both its establishment or modus operandi. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - As the mystery deepens around the COVID-19 National Command Council, the presidency insists there's nothing untoward or illegal about both its establishment or modus operandi. But not everyone is convinced. Several groups are gearing up to challenge the council’s powers and decisions in court. READ: COVID-19: Global cases top 4 million Until about a week ago, no-one seemed too bothered to know exactly how many people sit on the NCC, who they are, the criteria used to select them, and how they arrive at the far-reaching decisions they take on behalf of over 58-million people. The office of the President says a council of Cabinet ministers, joined by the chiefs of police and the army as well as a host of directors general, is nothing to worry about. Political Analyst Ralph Mathekga speaks to eNCA.#DStv403 Meanwhile, the Democratic Alliance is having none of it. READ: Mkhize: Govt concerned about growing number of COVID-19 cases in WC DA leader John Steenhuisen says, "we have to blindly trust a body called the National Command Council, a small group of ministers who don’t account to Parliament or anyone else. We asked for meeting minutes to clarify how they backtracked on the decision to ban cigarettes, and they claimed this was classified information." The DA is expected to file its court application this coming week. The total number of confirmed COVID-19 cases in South Africa has risen to 9,420. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinic